After fixes we now store ast::Attribute in the Delegation struct, which is passed from resolve to lowering stage. We add only attributes that can be inherited in `DelegationFnSig::to_inherit_attrs`. Then, we parse those attributes while lowering the delegation in order to obtain their hir::Attribute versions, and then use them to create inherited attributes. Thus, we provide a unified API for creating inherited attributes, whose original versions are in local or non-local crates.

Some considerations: 

- Now we clone AST attributes and store them in `DelegationFnSig::to_inherit_attrs`, however, we can try to pass [ast_index](https://github.com/aerooneqq/rust/blob/f5209000832c9d3bc29c91f4daef4ca9f28dc797/compiler/rustc_ast_lowering/src/lib.rs#L507C9-L507C19) to LoweringContext, then we can access AST nodes by LocalDefId through that `ast_index`, in this scenario we will not have to clone AST attributes and allocate memory for additional vector to store them, we will just obtain them and create their parsed (`hir::Attribute`) versions. However, I am not sure if exposing `ast_index` to LoweringContext is idiomatically correct;
- Maybe we can avoid parsing AST attributes, and try to create inherited attributes not from the original `hir::Attribute` but from `ast::Attribute`, however it will break the consistency of API for creating inherited attributes for local and non-local crates;
- For now I used dummy span and node id during attributes parsing, we can supply valid span and id through `DelegationFnSig` struct;
- Parsing attributes on the resolve level (in `ItemInfoCollector::collect_fn_info`) resulted in some failed tests, so for now parsing is inside lowering, we use methods for attributes parsing that are intendent to be used before lowering happened, which is basically our case.

