The motivation was:
When the user writes `map[&T]` for an **update**, they might expect to use `T` **after** since they only borrowed it during the map operation. When we suggest methods that take `T`, the compiler then encourage the user to use `.clone()` in order to use these methods.

In the case of the tests, a) they do not reuse the index after the map operation + b) even if they did,  they all use copy types: `u32` or `&str`

